title: Design and Implementation of a Wearable MC System
title_en: Design and Implementation of a Wearable MC System
abstract: 本研究はヘッドマウントディスプレイと音声認識を組み合わせたウェアラブル司会支援システムの設計と実装を扱っている。　本研究は表示デバイスの処理負荷を低減するために表示装置と外部計算機で処理を分担するアーキテクチャを採用し、台本照合のための文字単位の動的プログラミング照合やBGM対策を含む工学的手法を実装した。
abstract_en: This study addresses the design and implementation of a wearable master-of-ceremony support system that combines a head-mounted display with speech recognition. This study implements an architecture that offloads computation from the display device to an external PC and applies engineering techniques such as per-character dynamic programming matching and background-music countermeasures for script matching.
positioning_summary: 本研究はヘッドマウントディスプレイを用いたウェアラブル司会支援システムの設計と実装を扱っており、携帯機器と表示デバイス間の処理分担とリアルタイム表示の課題に対処する点に位置付けられる。　本研究はヘッドマウントディスプレイの処理負荷や既存の表示とウェブ連携の限界を解消することを目標としており、モバイル利用者やシステム開発者に影響する問題を対象としている。
positioning_summary_en: This study is positioned as work on the design and implementation of a wearable MC support system using a head-mounted display, addressing computation distribution and real-time display challenges. This study aims to resolve HMD processing load and limitations of existing HMD/Web integration, targeting issues that affect mobile users and system developers.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的はヘッドマウントディスプレイの処理負荷と台本照合に伴う運用上の負担を軽減することで、司会進行支援の実用性を高めることである。　本研究は発話が台本と一致するかをリアルタイムに判定して台本照合の失敗による司会者や運用者の負担を低減することを具体的な目的としている。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this study is to reduce HMD processing load and operational burdens from script matching in order to improve the practicality of MC support. The study specifically aims to perform real-time determination of whether utterances match the script to reduce burdens on presenters and operators from mismatches.
method_summary: 本研究はヘッドマウントディスプレイと外部計算機をLANで接続し、外部計算機側でFFTなどの重い処理を行って処理結果を表示装置へ返送する処理分担アーキテクチャを実装した。　本研究は音声認識エンジンとひらがな変換を用いて1文字ずつスライドさせるDPマッチングを行い、提示解像度約800×600の表示環境下でFFT処理やBGM対策を組み合わせて台本照合を実現している。
method_summary_en: The study implements an architecture that connects an HMD and an external PC over LAN, performing heavy computations such as FFT on the PC and returning results to the display device. The system uses a speech recognition engine with kana conversion and per-character sliding DP matching, combining FFT processing and background-music countermeasures in an approximately 800×600 display environment to achieve script matching.
evaluation_summary: 本研究の評価は音声認識スコアの正規化と閾値比較を用した台本判定手順と複数の音響条件を操作する実験手法で行われ、参加者数20名や各条件でのSNR値とBGMの有無を含む条件設定が用いられた。　本研究の評価では認識スコアの例として86, 91, 81が報告され、文字数22で最小スコアを正規化した値0.73を閾値比較に用い、条件によって84%や100%の検出率やSNR変化範囲-54.51dB〜-6.27dB、条件別成功率75%、90%、62.5%、0%などの結果が観察された。
evaluation_summary_en: The evaluation in this study used an experimental method that normalizes speech recognition scores and applies threshold comparison for script determination, manipulating multiple acoustic conditions including SNR levels, background music presence, and involving 20 participants. The evaluation observed recognition score examples of 86, 91, and 81, used a normalized minimum score of 0.73 for thresholding with 22 characters, and reported detection rates such as 84% and 100%, SNR change ranges from -54.51 dB to -6.27 dB, and per-condition success rates of 75%, 90%, 62.5%, and 0%.

Title: Design and Implementation of a Wearable MC System
Authors: Tomonari Okada, Tetsuya Yamamoto, Tsutomu Terada, Masahiko Tsukamoto
Year: 2009
Abstract: This study addresses the design and implementation of a wearable master-of-ceremony support system that combines a head-mounted display with speech recognition. This study implements an architecture that offloads computation from the display device to an external PC and applies engineering techniques such as per-character dynamic programming matching and background-music countermeasures for script matching.
Positioning Summary: This study is positioned as work on the design and implementation of a wearable MC support system using a head-mounted display, addressing computation distribution and real-time display challenges. This study aims to resolve HMD processing load and limitations of existing HMD/Web integration, targeting issues that affect mobile users and system developers.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this study is to reduce HMD processing load and operational burdens from script matching in order to improve the practicality of MC support. The study specifically aims to perform real-time determination of whether utterances match the script to reduce burdens on presenters and operators from mismatches.
Method Summary: The study implements an architecture that connects an HMD and an external PC over LAN, performing heavy computations such as FFT on the PC and returning results to the display device. The system uses a speech recognition engine with kana conversion and per-character sliding DP matching, combining FFT processing and background-music countermeasures in an approximately 800×600 display environment to achieve script matching.
Evaluation Summary: The evaluation in this study used an experimental method that normalizes speech recognition scores and applies threshold comparison for script determination, manipulating multiple acoustic conditions including SNR levels, background music presence, and involving 20 participants. The evaluation observed recognition score examples of 86, 91, and 81, used a normalized minimum score of 0.73 for thresholding with 22 characters, and reported detection rates such as 84% and 100%, SNR change ranges from -54.51 dB to -6.27 dB, and per-condition success rates of 75%, 90%, 62.5%, and 0%.
